{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{BLP sources|date=August 2010}} {{Infobox person | name = Hans Melchers | image = | caption = | birth_name = Hans Daniel Melchers<ref name="Wealth-X" /> | birth_date = {{birth-date and age|18 May 1938}}<ref name="Wealth-X" /> | birth_place = [[Apeldoorn]], Netherlands | residence = [[Vorden]], Netherlands<ref name="Forbes 2016 The World's Billionaires" /> | nationality = Dutch | known_for = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = | know_for = | networth = {{nowrap|[[United States dollar|US$]]2.4 billion (''[[Forbes]]'' 2016)<ref name="Forbes 2016 The World's Billionaires" />}} | spouse = married<ref name="Forbes 2016 The World's Billionaires" /> | partner = | children = 2<ref name="Forbes 2016 The World's Billionaires" /> | parents = | relatives = | website = }}
'''Hans Daniel Melchers''' (born 18 May 1938 in [[Apeldoorn]])<ref name="Wealth-X">{{cite web |url=http://www.wealthx.com/articles/2015/hans-daniel-melchers/ |title=Billionaires: Hans Daniel MELCHERS |publisher=[[Wealth-X]] |accessdate=2017-01-02}}</ref> is a Dutch businessman. Melchers founded [[Melchemie Holland BV]],<ref name="Bloomberg">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=afVxtZTwmd1A&refer=europe |title=Dutch Police Probe Seizure of Millionaire's Daughter |date=14 September 2005 |newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=6 August 2010}}</ref> and is major (15%) shareholder in HAL Investments BV. With a total capital of €460 million, Melchers reached a 36th spot in the 2005 edition of the [[Quote 500]]-list of the most wealthy Dutch.
On the ''[[Forbes]]'' 2016 list of the world's billionaires, he was ranked #722 with a net worth of [[United States dollar|US$]]2.4 billion.<ref name="Forbes 2016 The World's Billionaires">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/hans-melchers/?list=billionaires |title=The World's Billionaires (2016 ranking): #722 Hans Melchers |date=1 March 2016 |work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=2017-01-02}}</ref>
Since the early 1990s until 2007, Melchers was a major sponsor of the Dutch Bridge Federation (NBB). In 2008 Melchers started his own professional bridge team. He "provided major funding for the 2011 world bridge championship held in the Netherlands"<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/profile/hans-melchers/ "#891 Hans Melcher"]. ''The World's Billionaires''. Forbes. Retrieved 9 June 2014.</ref> (in [[Veldhoven]], hosted by NBB).
His daughter, [[Claudia Melchers|Claudia]], was the victim of a [[kidnap]]ping in September 2005.<ref name="Bloomberg" /> She was released after two days of confinement.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aBkKCFkPWKdc&refer=europe |title=Abductors of Dutch Millionaire's Daughter Wanted Cocaine Ransom |date=15 September 2005 |newspaper=Bloomberg News |accessdate=6 August 2010}}</ref>
