{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Lucien Ebata<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Lucien Ebata at Paris Signing.jpg <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = Lucien Ebata at Paris Signing, October 2013 | birth_name = <!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|03|12}} | baptism_date = | birth_place = | monuments = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = [[Republic of the Congo]] and [[Canada]] | education = | alma_mater = {{Plainlist|*[[University of Havana]] *[[University of Ottawa]] *[[University of Montreal]]}} | occupation = | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = [[:fr:Forbes Afrique|Forbes Afrique]]{{Plainlist}} [[Orion Group SA]] | home_town = Ollombo, Republic of the Congo | salary = | net_worth = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | height = <!-- {{height|m=}} --> | weight = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} --> | television = | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | movement = | opponents = | boards = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | partner = Philo Ebata<!-- unmarried life partner; use ''Name (1950–present)'' --> | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | website = {{URL|http://www.lucienebata.com}}<!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | footnotes = | box_width = }}
'''Lucien Ebata''' (born 12 March 1969, Ollombo, [[Republic of the Congo]]) is a Congolese-Canadian businessman and publisher. He is the founder and CEO of [[Orion Group SA|Orion Oil]], and publisher of ''[[:fr:Forbes Afrique|Forbes Afrique]]''.<ref> {{cite news |url=http://www.voanews.com/content/new-forbes-magazine-to-highlight-successful-africa-business-says-official/1514195.html |title=New Forbes Magazine to Highlight Successful Africa Business |work=[[Voice of America]] |date=24 September 2012 |first=Peter|last=Clottey }}</ref>
==Biography== Ebata was born in Ollombo, [[Republic of the Congo]], on 12 March 1969. He emigrated to [[Cuba]] where he attained a law degree from the [[University of Havana]] in 1994. He then emigrated to [[Canada]] and completed master's degree studies in Commercial Law at the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1996, and received an [[LLM]] degree in Business Law from the [[University of Montreal]] in 2004.
==Career== Ebata was variously employed at the Canadian [[Ministry of Natural Resources (Ontario)|Ministry of Natural Resources]], [[Ministry of Human Resources (Canada)|Ministry of Human Resources]], [[Commission for Public Service (Canada)|Commission for Public Service]] and [[Environment Canada|Ministry of Environment]].
Ebata left government service to form a private firm specializing in insurance and taxation, representing clients in the [[Tax Court of Canada]]. Between 2001 and 2004, he shifted his attention to lobbying on behalf of businesses and foreign governments.
Several years later, he founded the [[Orion Group SA]] and focused its activities on the trading of petroleum products, i.e. the purchase / resale of crude and refined petroleum products, mainly on the African continent. He later expanded the scope of the activities of his group to the leasing of aircraft and chauffeur driven cars in Africa and Europe.
Ebata launched ''[[:fr:Forbes Afrique|Forbes Afrique]]'' on 24 July 2012, the [[Francophone]] African version of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, specializing in economic fortunes and ranking information.
==Memberships== * Association of French Speaking Jurists of Ontario * Association of University Students in Havana (Past President) * Federation of Congolese Students in Canada (Past President) * ''Journal of Residents of the University of Ottawa'' (past editor) * Historical Society of the Americas * Association of Friends of [[the Louvre]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Party in Paris: Gypsy Queens rock Luxembourg Palace but Duran Duran's Nick Rhodes won't sing|url=http://houston.culturemap.com/news/society/06-18-13-party-in-paris-gypsy-queens-rock-luxembourg-palace-but-duran-durans-nick-rhodes-wont-sing/|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=Culturemap Houston|date=17 June 2013|author=CLIFFORD PUGH}}</ref>
